<paragraph blockId="7.[136,1452,482,796]" pageId="7" pageNumber="288">
Upon analysing the evidence available, we concluded that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Skottsberg" authorityYear="1953" box="[875,1003,662,688]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Margyricarpus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="7" pageNumber="288" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dyginus">
<emphasis box="[875,1003,662,688]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="288">M. dyginus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
merits to be recognised at the species rank. In addition to the bicarpellate gynoecium, which was duly pointed by Skottsberg, the leaf morphology is very distinctive. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Skottsberg" authorityYear="1953" box="[269,535,734,760]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Margyricarpus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="7" pageNumber="288" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dyginus">
<emphasis box="[269,535,734,760]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="288">Margyricarpus dyginus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has long and falciform folioles, and has a restrictive insular distribution, being endemic to Juan Fernández, 
<collectingCountry box="[456,520,770,796]" name="Chile" pageId="7" pageNumber="288">Chile</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
